    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nStarting from a new buffer or a buffer loaded from an empty file, `nvim_buf_get_offset` keeps reporting the offset of the first line (index 0) as -1. This stops after inserting a new line.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n- Create a new buffer (`:new`)\r\n- `vim.api.nvim_buf_get_offset(0, 0)` returns `-1`.\r\n- Start adding characters in the first line, for instance input `Axxx<Esc>`. Insert mode can be entered and exited any number of times.\r\n- After each change, the offset of the first line is still `-1`. This can be verified using `:=` in normal mode, or in a callback as characters are inserted.\r\n- Input `<Enter>`. From this point on, `vim.api.nvim_buf_get_offset(0, 0)` returns `0`.\r\n- The same happens when using `:e` on an empty file.\r\n- Cannot reproduce on non-empty files, including files which do not contain `\\n`.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`vim.api.nvim_buf_get_offset(0, 0)` should always return `0`; or at least not change its mind.\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.9.1\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nn/a\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nn/a\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nn/a\n\n### Installation\n\nofficial Arch extra repository",
    "closed_at": "2023-08-30T11:14:31Z",
